After seeing Webern's Op. 5 manuscript in mid-1909, Schoenberg described a rather Webernian aesthetic, which invigorated his own music, in a letter toFerruccio Busoni: "Harmony is expression and nothing else. ... Away withPathos! Away withprotracted ten-tonscores .... My music must be brief. Concise!In two notes: not built, but expressed!! And the results I wish for: no stylized and sterile protracted emotion. People are not like that: it is impossible for a person to have only one sensation at a time. One has thousands simultaneously. ... And this variegation, this multifariousness, this illogicality which our senses demonstrate, the illogicality presented by their interactions, set forth by some mounting rush of blood, by some reaction of the senses or the nerves, this I should like to have in my music."
